  } as CSSProperties;

  return (
    <div
      style={optionStyles}
      className="flex overflow-hidden rounded border border-grey-5 bg-grey-5 p-1"
      role="radiogroup"
    >
      {options.map((option) => (
        <div key={option.key} className="flex-1">
          <input
            type="radio"
            name={name}
            value={option.key}
            checked={option.isSelected}
            onChange={option.onSelect}
            className="peer sr-only" // Added peer class
            data-testid={testIdPrefix + option.key}
            data-test-is-selected={option.isSelected}
          />
          <label
            htmlFor={option.key}
            className={cx(
              'rounded-md block h-full',
              'cursor-pointer py-2',
              'peer-focus:ring-2 peer-focus:ring-digital peer-focus:ring-offset-1', // Added focus styles
              option.isSelected && 'bg-[var(--background-color)] text-white',
              !option.isSelected && 'bg-white text-grey-80',
            )}
          >
            <p className="my-0 text-center text-sm font-semibold md:text-[18px]">
              {option.label}
              {option.labelSecondary && (
                <span
                  className={cx(
                    'block text-sm font-normal',
                    option.isSelected && 'text-white',
                    !option.isSelected && 'text-grey-45',
                  )}
                >
                  {option.labelSecondary}
                </span>
              )}
            </p>
          </label>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}
```

Key changes:
1. Added a wrapper `div` for each option
2. Moved the `input` before the `label`
3. Added `peer` class to the input
4. Added `peer-focus:ring-*` classes to the label
5. Added `htmlFor` to connect the label with input
6. Changed label to `block` display

Now the peer selector will work properly to style the label when the input is focused. The visual appearance should remain the same, but you'll get the focus ring effect when the input is focused.
